PlayerState now carries the procedural settling slice we need to track expansion drive: a target settlement count plus up to four settler and four scout unit indices. That sits beside the older per-seat flags (AI-controlled, active, civ index) and economy/fog fields, so settling progress is meant to live on the same seat array GameSetup already allocates in GameState. Today those new fields are declaration-only; setup still zeroes m_ai_controlled and does not bind settlers into the slots when civs spawn. GameLoop itself only increments the turn counter and emits trace events—it does not yet call CityTurnHandler, unit movement, or any AI settle policy—so the loop is the natural ownership point but still an empty shell for this feature.

Settlement opportunity sensing already exists under ai_proc as SenseMakingSettlerPt (mk1/mk2). select() gathers candidate land tiles in a min/max distance band from source points using ownership-aware passability, and pick() ranks candidates with land-to-water distance context toward a capital-like anchor. The API speaks MapTerrainData and SpgCoordPair, not GameArraySimple/GameState directly, so a thin adapter from the live map and city/capital positions will be required before the game loop can call it per AI seat. Testers under ai_proc already exercise iterative multi-player picks and PPM overlays, which is a good reference for how candidates should look before we wire production and movement.

Long-range tile walking for a settler once a target exists is covered by ai_pathing/walk_general: SectorNetwork plus SectorNetworkRouter give center-to-center land hops, and PointSeqFloodWalker follows that corridor with per-waypoint local floods. That stack is proven on random same-mass endpoints but is not yet a per-unit movement service inside GameState (no persistent walker per settler, no turn-budgeted step(), no unit-array apply). CityTurnHandler can finish builds today but does not choose settlers or notify PlayerState when one appears; unit turns are not looped at all. The near-term integration path is therefore: fill and maintain PlayerState settler slots on spawn/build, sense a settle tile when an AI seat needs expansion, start a flood walk to that tile, and advance one movement quantum per game turn until arrival and found-city.
